@c    THE PROPHECY OF DANIEL



@c    DANIEL, whose name signifies THE JUDGMENT OF GOD, was of the royal
@c    blood of the kings of Juda:  and one of those that were first of all
@c    carried away into captivity.  He was so renowned for wisdom and
@c    knowledge, that it became a proverb among the Babylonians, AS WISE AS
@c    DANIEL (Ezech. 28.3).  And his holiness was so great from his very
@c    childhood, that at the time when he was as yet but a young man, he is
@c    joined by the SPIRIT of GOD with NOE and JOB, as three persons most
@c    eminent for virtue and sanctity, Ezech. 14.  He is not commonly numbered
@c    by the Hebrews among THE PROPHETS:  because he lived at court, and in
@c    high station in the world:  but if we consider his many clear
@c    predictions of things to come, we shall find that no one better
@c    deserves the name and title of A PROPHET:  which also has been given him
@c    by the SON of GOD himself, Matt. 24, Mark 13., Luke 21.



@c    Daniel Chapter 1


@c    Daniel and his companions are taken into the palace of the king of
@c    Babylon:  they abstain from his meat and wine, and succeed better with
@c    pulse and water.  Their excellence and wisdom.

@c    1:1. In the third year of the reign of Joakim, king of Juda,
@c    Nabuchodonosor, king of Babylon, came to Jerusalem, and beseiged it.

@c    1:2. And the Lord delivered into his hands Joakim, the king of Juda,
@c    and part of the vessels of the house of God:  and he carried them away
@c    into the land of Sennaar, to the house of his god, and the vessels he
@c    brought into the treasure house of his god.

@c    His god. . .Bel or Belus, the principal idol of the Chaldeans.

@c    1:3. And the king spoke to Asphenez, the master of the eunuchs, that he
@c    should bring in some of the children of Israel, and of the king's seed,
@c    and of the princes,

@c    1:4. Children in whom there was no blemish, well favoured, and skilful
@c    in all wisdom, acute in knowledge, and instructed in science, and such
@c    as might stand in the king's palace, that he might teach them the
@c    learning, and tongue of the Chaldeans.

@c    1:5. And the king appointed them a daily provision, of his own meat,
@c    and of the wine of which he drank himself, that being nourished three
@c    years, afterwards they might stand before the king.

@c    1:6. Now there was among them of the children of Juda, Daniel, Ananias,
@c    Misael, and Azarias.

@c    1:7. And the master of the eunuchs gave them names:  to Daniel,
@c    Baltassar:  to Ananias, Sidrach:  to Misael, Misach:  and to Azarias,
@c    Abdenago.

@c    1:8. But Daniel purposed in his heart that he would not be defiled with
@c    the king's table, nor with the wine which he drank:  and he requested
@c    the master of the eunuchs that he might not be defiled.

@c    Be defiled, etc. . .Viz., either by eating meat forbidden by the law, or
@c    which had before been offered to idols.

@c    1:9. And God gave to Daniel grace and mercy in the sight of the prince
@c    of the eunuchs.

@c    1:10. And the prince of the eunuchs said to Daniel:  I fear my lord, the
@c    king, who hath appointed you meat and drink:  who if he should see your
@c    faces leaner than those of the other youths, your equals, you shall
@c    endanger my head to the king.

@c    1:11. And Daniel said to Malasar, whom the prince of the eunuchs had
@c    appointed over Daniel, Ananias, Misael, and Azarias:

@c    1:12. Try, I beseech thee, thy servants for ten days, and let pulse be
@c    given us to eat, and water to drink:

@c    Pulse. . .That is, pease, beans, and such like.

@c    1:13. And look upon our faces, and the faces of the children that eat
@c    of the king's meat:  and as thou shalt see, deal with thy servants.

@c    1:14. And when he had heard these words, he tried them for ten days.

@c    1:15. And after ten days, their faces appeared fairer and fatter than
@c    all the children that ate of the king's meat.

@c    1:16. So Malasar took their portions, and the wine that they should
@c    drink:  and he gave them pulse.

@c    1:17. And to these children God gave knowledge, and understanding in
@c    every book, and wisdom:  but to Daniel the understanding also of all
@c    visions and dreams.

@c    1:18. And when the days were ended, after which the king had ordered
@c    they should be brought in:  the prince of the eunuchs brought them in
@c    before Nabuchodonosor.

@c    1:19. And when the king had spoken to them, there were not found among
@c    them all such as Daniel, Ananias, Misael, and Azarias:  and they stood
@c    in the king's presence.

@c    1:20. And in all matters of wisdom and understanding, that the king
@c    enquired of them, he found them ten times better than all the diviners,
@c    and wise men, that were in all his kingdom.

@c    1:21. And Daniel continued even to the first year of king Cyrus.



@c    Daniel Chapter 2


@c    Daniel, by divine revelation, declares the dream of Nabuchodonosor, and
@c    the interpretation of it.  He is highly honoured by the king.

@c    2:1. In the second year of the reign of Nabuchodonosor, Nabuchodonosor
@c    had a dream, and his spirit was terrified, and his dream went out of
@c    his mind.

@c    The second year. . .Viz., from the death of his father Nabopolassar; for
@c    he had reigned before as partner with his father in the empire.

@c    2:2. Then the king commanded to call together the diviners and the wise
@c    men, and the magicians, and the Chaldeans:  to declare to the king his
@c    dreams:  so they came and stood before the king.

@c    The Chaldeeans. . .That is, the astrologers, that pretended to divine by
@c    stars.

@c    2:3. And the king said to them:  I saw a dream:  and being troubled in
@c    mind I know not what I saw.

@c    2:4. And the Chaldeans answered the king in Syriac:  O king, live for
@c    ever:  tell to thy servants thy dream, and we will declare the
@c    interpretation thereof.

@c    2:5. And the king, answering, said to the Chaldeans:  The thing is gone
@c    out of my mind:  unless you tell me the dream, and the meaning thereof,
@c    you shall be put to death, and your houses shall be confiscated.

@c    2:6. but if you tell the dream, and the meaning of it, you shall
@c    receive of me rewards, and gifts, and great honour:  therefore, tell me
@c    the dream, and the interpretation thereof.

@c    2:7. They answered again and said:  Let the king tell his servants the
@c    dream, and we will declare the interpretation of it.

@c    2:8. The king answered and said:  I know for certain, that you seek to
@c    gain time, since you know that the thing is gone from me.

@c    2:9. If, therefore, you tell me not the dream, there is one sentence
@c    concerning you, that you have also framed a lying interpretation, and
@c    full of deceit, to speak before me till the time pass away.  Tell me,
@c    therefore, the dream, that I may know that you also give a true
@c    interpretation thereof.

@c    2:10. Then the Chaldeans answered before the king, and said:  There is
@c    no man upon earth, that can accomplish thy word, O king; neither doth
@c    any king, though great and mighty, ask such a thing of any diviner, or
@c    wise man, or Chaldean.

@c    2:11. For the thing that thou asketh, O king, is difficult:  nor can any
@c    one be found that can shew it before the king, except the gods, whose
@c    conversation is not with men.

@c    2:12. Upon hearing this, the king in fury, and in great wrath,
@c    commanded that all the wise men of Babylon should be put to death.

@c    2:13. And the decree being gone forth, the wise men were slain:  and
@c    Daniel and his companions were sought for, to be put to death.

@c    2:14. Then Daniel inquired concerning the law and the sentence, of
@c    Arioch, the general of the king's army, who was gone forth to kill the
@c    wise men of Babylon.

@c    2:15. And he asked him that had received the orders of the king, why so
@c    cruel a sentence was gone forth from the face of the king.  And when
@c    Arioch had told the matter to Daniel,

@c    2:16. Daniel went in, and desired of the king, that he would give him
@c    time to resolve the question, and declare it to the king.

@c    2:17. And he went into his house, and told the matter to Ananias, and
@c    Misael, and Azarias, his companions:

@c    2:18. To the end that they should ask mercy at the face of the God of
@c    heaven, concerning this secret, and that Daniel and his companions
@c    might not perish with the rest of the wise men of Babylon.

@c    2:19. Then was the mystery revealed to Daniel by a vision in the night:
@c    and Daniel blessed the God of heaven,

@c    2:20. And speaking, he said:  Blessed be the name of the Lord from
@c    eternity and for evermore:  for wisdom and fortitude are his.

@c    2:21. And he changeth times and ages:  taketh away kingdoms, and
@c    establisheth them:  giveth wisdom to the wise, and knowledge to them
@c    that have understanding:

@c    2:22. He revealeth deep and hidden things, and knoweth what is in
@c    darkness:  and light is with him.

@c    2:23. To thee, O God of our fathers, I give thanks, and I praise thee:
@c    because thou hast given me wisdom and strength:  and now thou hast shewn
@c    me what we desired of thee, for thou hast made known to us the king's
@c    discourse.

@c    2:24. After this Daniel went in to Arioch, to whom the king had given
@c    orders to destroy the wise men of Babylon, and he spoke thus to him:
@c    Destroy not the wise men of Babylon:  bring me in before the king, and I
@c    will tell the solution to the king.

@c    2:25. Then Arioch in haste brought in Daniel to the king, and said to
@c    him:  I have found a man of the children of the captivity of Juda, that
@c    will resolve the question to the king.

@c    2:26. The king answered, and said to Daniel, whose name was Baltassar:
@c    Thinkest thou indeed that thou canst tell me the dream that I saw, and
@c    the interpretation thereof?

@c    2:27. And Daniel made answer before the king, and said:  The secret that
@c    the king desireth to know, none of the wise men, or the philosophers,
@c    or the diviners, or the soothsayers, can declare to the king.

@c    2:28. But there is a God in heaven that revealeth mysteries, who hath
@c    shewn to thee, O king Nabuchodonosor, what is to come to pass in the
@c    latter times.  Thy dream, and the visions of thy head upon thy bed, are
@c    these:

@c    2:29. Thou, O king, didst begin to think in thy bed, what should come
@c    to pass hereafter:  and he that revealeth mysteries shewed thee what
@c    shall come to pass.

@c    2:30. To me also this secret is revealed, not by any wisdom that I have
@c    more than all men alive:  but that the interpretation might be made
@c    manifest to the king, and thou mightest know the thought of thy mind.

@c    2:31. Thou, O king, sawest, and behold there was as it were a great
@c    statue:  this statue, which was great and high, tall of stature, stood
@c    before thee, and the look thereof was terrible.

@c    2:32. The head of this statue was of fine gold, but the breast and the
@c    arms of silver, and the belly and the thighs of brass.

@c    2:33. And the legs of iron, the feet part of iron and part of clay.

@c    2:34. Thus thou sawest, till a stone was cut out of a mountain without
@c    hands:  and it struck the statue upon the feet thereof that were of iron
@c    and clay, and broke them in pieces.

@c    2:35. Then was the iron, the clay, the brass, the silver, and the gold
@c    broken to pieces together, and became like the chaff of a summer's
@c    threshing floor, and they were carried away by the wind:  and there was
@c    no place found for them:  but the stone that struck the statue became a
@c    great mountain, and filled the whole earth.

@c    2:36. This is the dream:  we will also tell the interpretation thereof
@c    before thee, O king.

@c    2:37. Thou art a king of kings:  and the God of heaven hath given thee a
@c    kingdom, and strength, and power, and glory:

@c    2:38. And all places wherein the children of men, and the beasts of the
@c    field do dwell:  he hath also given the birds of the air into thy hand,
@c    and hath put all things under thy power:  thou, therefore, art the head
@c    of gold.

@c    2:39. And after thee shall rise up another kingdom, inferior to thee,
@c    of silver:  and another third kingdom of brass, which shall rule over
@c    all the world.

@c    Another kingdom. . .Viz., that of the Medes and Persians.  Ibid.  Third
@c    kingdom. . .Viz., that of Alexander the Great.

@c    2:40. And the fourth kingdom shall be as iron.  As iron breaketh into
@c    pieces, and subdueth all things, so shall that break, and destroy all
@c    these.

@c    The fourth kingdom, etc. . .Some understand this of the successors of
@c    Alexander, the kings of Syria and Egypt, others of the Roman empire,
@c    and its civil wars.

@c    2:41. And whereas thou sawest the feet, and the toes, part of potter's
@c    clay, and part of iron:  the kingdom shall be divided, but yet it shall
@c    take its origin from the iron, according as thou sawest the iron mixed
@c    with the miry clay.

@c    2:42. And as the toes of the feet were part of iron, and part of clay:
@c    the kingdom shall be partly strong, and partly broken.

@c    2:43. And whereas thou sawest the iron mixed with miry clay, they shall
@c    be mingled indeed together with the seed of man, but they shall not
@c    stick fast one to another, as iron cannot be mixed with clay.

@c    2:44. But in the days of those kingdoms, the God of heaven will set up
@c    a kingdom that shall never by destroyed, and his kingdom shall not be
@c    delivered up to another people:  and it shall break in pieces, and shall
@c    consume all these kingdoms:  and itself shall stand for ever.

@c    A kingdom. . .Viz., the kingdom of Christ in the Catholic Church which
@c    cannot be destroyed.

@c    2:45. According as thou sawest, that the stone was cut out of the
@c    mountain without hands, and broke in pieces the clay and the iron, and
@c    the brass, and the silver, and the gold, the great God hath shewn the
@c    king what shall come to pass hereafter, and the dream is true, and the
@c    interpretation thereof is faithful.

@c    2:46. Then king Nabuchodonosor fell on his face, and worshipped Daniel,
@c    and commanded that they should offer in sacrifice to him victims and
@c    incense.

@c    2:47. And the king spoke to Daniel, and said:  Verily, your God is the
@c    God of gods, and Lord of kings, and a revealer of hidden things:  seeing
@c    thou couldst discover this secret.

@c    2:48. Then the king advanced Daniel to a high station, and gave him
@c    many and great gifts:  and he made him governor over all the provinces
@c    of Babylon:  and chief of the magistrates over all the wise men of
@c    Babylon.

@c    2:49. And Daniel requested of the king, and he appointed Sidrach,
@c    Misach, and Abdenago, over the works of the province of Babylon:  but
@c    Daniel himself was in the king's palace.



@c    Daniel Chapter 3


@c    Nabuchodonosor set up a golden statue; which he commands all to adore:
@c    the three children for refusing to do it are cast into the fiery
@c    furnace; but are not hurt by the flames.  Their prayer and canticle of
@c    praise.

@c    3:1. King Nabuchodonosor made a statue of gold, of sixty cubits high,
@c    and six cubits broad, and he set it up in the plain of Dura, of the
@c    province of Babylon.

@c    3:2. Then Nabuchodonosor, the king, sent to call together the nobles,
@c    the magistrates, and the judges, the captains, the rulers, and
@c    governors, and all the chief men of the provinces, to come to the
@c    dedication of the statue which king Nabuchodonosor had set up.

@c    3:3. Then the nobles, the magistrates, and the judges, the captains,
@c    and rulers, and the great men that were placed in authority, and all
@c    the princes of the provinces, were gathered together to come to the
@c    dedication of the statue, which king Nabuchodonosor had set up.  And
@c    they stood before the statue which king Nabuchodonosor had set up.

@c    3:4. Then a herald cried with a strong voice:  To you it is commanded, O
@c    nations, tribes and languages:

@c    3:5. That in the hour that you shall hear the sound of the trumpet, and
@c    of the flute, and of the harp, of the sackbut, and of the psaltery, and
@c    of the symphony, and of all kind of music, ye fall down and adore the
@c    golden statue which king Nabuchodonosor hath set up.

@c    3:6. But if any man shall not fall down and adore, he shall the same
@c    hour be cast into a furnace of burning fire.

@c    3:7. Upon this, therefore, at the time when all the people heard the
@c    sound of the trumpet, the flute, and the harp, of the sackbut, and the
@c    psaltery, of the symphony, and of all kind of music, all the nations,
@c    tribes, and languages fell down and adored the golden statue which king
@c    Nabuchodonosor had set up.

@c    3:8. And presently at that very time some Chaldeans came and accused
@c    the Jews,

@c    3:9. And said to king Nabuchodonosor:  O king, live for ever:

@c    3:10. Thou, O king, hast made a decree, that every man that shall hear
@c    the sound of the trumpet, the flute, and the harp, of the sackbut, and
@c    the psaltery, of the symphony, and of all kind of music, shall
@c    prostrate himself, and adore the golden statue:

@c    3:11. And that if any man shall not fall down and adore, he should be
@c    cast into a furnace of burning fire.

@c    3:12. Now there are certain Jews, whom thou hast set over the works of
@c    the province of Babylon, Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago:  these men, O
@c    king, have slighted thy decree:  they worship not thy gods, nor do they
@c    adore the golden statue which thou hast set up.

@c    3:13. Then Nabuchodonosor in fury, and in wrath, commanded that
@c    Sidrach, Misach, ad Abdenago should be brought:  who immediately were
@c    brought before the king.

@c    3:14. And Nabuchodonosor, the king, spoke to them, and said:  Is it
@c    true, O Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago, that you do not worship my gods,
@c    nor adore the golden statue that I have set up?

@c    3:15. Now, therefore, if you be ready, at what hour soever, you shall
@c    hear the sound of the trumpet, flute, harp, sackbut, and psaltery, and
@c    symphony, and of all kind of music, prostrate yourselves, and adore the
@c    statue which I have made:  but if you do not adore, you shall be cast
@c    the same hour into the furnace of burning fire:  and who is the God that
@c    shall deliver you out of my hand?

@c    3:16. Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago, answered, and said to king
@c    Nabuchodonosor:  We have no occasion to answer thee concerning this
@c    matter.

@c    3:17. For behold our God, whom we worship, is able to save us from the
@c    furnace of burning fire, and to deliver us out of thy hands, O king.

@c    3:18. But if he will not, be it known to thee, O king, that we will not
@c    worship thy gods, nor adore the golden statue which thou hast set up.

@c    3:19. Then was Nabuchodonosor filled with fury:  and the countenance of
@c    his face was changed against Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago, and he
@c    commanded that the furnace should be heated seven times more than it
@c    had been accustomed to be heated.

@c    3:20. And he commanded the strongest men that were in his army, to bind
@c    the feet of Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago, and to cast them into the
@c    furnace of burning fire.

@c    3:21. And immediately these men were bound, and were cast into the
@c    furnace of burning fire, with their coats, and their caps, and their
@c    shoes, and their garments.

@c    3:22. For the king's commandment was urgent, and the furnace was heated
@c    exceedingly.  And the flame of the fire slew those men that had cast in
@c    Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago.

@c    3:23. But these three men, that is, Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago, fell
@c    down bound in the midst of the furnace of burning fire.

@c    3:24. And they walked in the midst of the flame, praising God, and
@c    blessing the Lord.

@c    And they walked, etc. . .Here St. Jerome takes notice, that from this
@c    verse, to ver. 91, was not in the Hebrew in his time.  But as it was in
@c    all the Greek Bibles, (which were originally translated from the
@c    Hebrew,) it is more than probable that it had been formerly in the
@c    Hebrew or rather in the Chaldaic, in which the book of Daniel was
@c    written.  But this is certain:  that it is, and has been of old, received
@c    by the church, and read as canonical scripture in her liturgy, and
@c    divine offices.

@c    3:25. Then Azarias standing up, prayed in this manner, and opening his
@c    mouth in the midst of the fire, he said:

@c    3:26. Blessed art thou, O Lord, the God of our fathers, and thy name is
@c    worthy of praise, and glorious for ever:

@c    3:27. For thou art just in all that thou hast done to us, and all thy
@c    works are true, and thy ways right, and all thy judgments true.

@c    3:28. For thou hast executed true judgments in all the things that thou
@c    hast brought upon us, and upon Jerusalem, the holy city of our fathers:
@c    for according to truth and judgment, thou hast brought all these things
@c    upon us for our sins.

@c    3:29. For we have sinned, and committed iniquity, departing from thee:
@c    and we have trespassed in all things:

@c    3:30. And we have not hearkened to thy commandments, nor have we
@c    observed nor done as thou hadst commanded us, that it might go well
@c    with us.

@c    3:31. Wherefore, all that thou hast brought upon us, and every thing
@c    that thou hast done to us, thou hast done in true judgment:

@c    3:32. And thou hast delivered us into the hands of our enemies that are
@c    unjust, and most wicked, and prevaricators, and to a king unjust, and
@c    most wicked beyond all that are upon the earth.

@c    3:33. And now we cannot open our mouths:  we are become a shame, and a
@c    reproach to thy servants, and to them that worship thee.

@c    3:34. Deliver us not up for ever, we beseech thee, for thy name's sake,
@c    and abolish not thy covenant.

@c    3:35. And take not away thy mercy from us, for the sake of Abraham, thy
@c    beloved, and Isaac, thy servant, and Israel, thy holy one:

@c    3:36. To whom thou hast spoken, promising that thou wouldst multiply
@c    their seed as the stars of heaven, and as the sand that is on the sea
@c    shore.

@c    3:37. For we, O Lord, are diminished more than any nation, and are
@c    brought low in all the earth this day for our sins.

@c    3:38. Neither is there at this time prince, or leader, or prophet, or
@c    holocaust, or sacrifice, or oblation, or incense, or place of first
@c    fruits before thee,

@c    3:39. That we may find thy mercy:  nevertheless, in a contrite heart and
@c    humble spirit let us be accepted.

@c    3:40. As in holocausts of rams, and bullocks, and as in thousands of
@c    fat lambs:  so let our sacrifice be made in thy sight this day, that it
@c    may please thee:  for there is no confusion to them that trust in thee.

@c    3:41. And now we follow thee with all our heart, and we fear thee, and
@c    seek thy face.

@c    3:42. Put us not to confusion, but deal with us according to thy
@c    meekness, and according to the multitude of thy mercies.

@c    3:43. And deliver us, according to thy wonderful works, and give glory
@c    to thy name, O Lord:

@c    3:44. And let all them be confounded that shew evils to thy servants,
@c    let them be confounded in all thy might, and let their strength be
@c    broken:

@c    3:45. And let them know that thou art the Lord, the only God, and
@c    glorious over all the world.

@c    3:46. Now the king's servants that had cast them in, ceased not to heat
@c    the furnace with brimstone and tow, and pitch, and dry sticks,

@c    3:47. And the flame mounted up above the furnace nine and forth cubits:

@c    3:48. And it broke forth, and burnt such of the Chaldeans as it found
@c    near the furnace.

@c    3:49. But the angel of the Lord went down with Azarias and his
@c    companions into the furnace:  and he drove the flame of the fire out of
@c    the furnace,

@c    3:50. And made the midst of the furnace like the blowing of a wind
@c    bringing dew, and the fire touched them not at all, nor troubled them,
@c    nor did them any harm.

@c    3:51. Then these three, as with one mouth, praised and glorified and
@c    blessed God, in the furnace, saying:

@c    3:52. Blessed art thou, O Lord, the God of our fathers; and worthy to
@c    be praised, and glorified, and exalted above all for ever:  and blessed
@c    is the holy name of thy glory:  and worthy to be praised and exalted
@c    above all, in all ages.

@c    3:53. Blessed art thou in the holy temple of thy glory:  and exceedingly
@c    to be praised and exalted above all for ever.

@c    3:55. Blessed art thou that beholdest the depths, and sittest upon the
@c    cherubims:  and worthy to be praised and exalted above all for ever.

@c    3:56. Blessed art thou in the firmament of heaven:  and worthy of
@c    praise, and glorious for ever.

@c    3:57. All ye works of the Lord, bless the Lord:  praise and exalt him
@c    above all for ever.

@c    3:58. O ye angels of the Lord, bless the Lord:  praise and exalt him
@c    above all for ever.

@c    3:59. O ye heavens, bless the Lord:  praise and exalt him above all for
@c    ever.

@c    3:60. O all ye waters that are above the heavens, bless the Lord:
@c    praise and exalt him above all for ever.

